do is segment our audiences,

20
00:01:18.944 --> 00:01:22.777
which is a marketing term but
actually very useful.

21
00:01:22.777 --> 00:01:27.515
If you start thinking of your audiences
as just big chunks of people and

22
00:01:27.515 --> 00:01:31.769
there's this kind of vague idea
of the kind of person they are,

23
00:01:31.769 --> 00:01:37.257
then that lacks the clarity that you need
and it needs to be done better than that.

24
00:01:37.257 --> 00:01:42.107
However, the way that I would suggest
that you segment your audiences maybe

25
00:01:42.107 --> 00:01:46.678
a little bit different from how many
people think about segmentation.

26
00:01:46.678 --> 00:01:51.540
Because most people when they think
about segmentation are thinking about it

27
00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:53.570
from a marketing perspective.

28
00:01:53.570 --> 00:01:58.211
So marketing people tend to
segment around demographics or

29
00:01:58.211 --> 00:02:03.328
socioeconomic groups or
interest groups and that kind of thing.

30
00:02:03.328 --> 00:02:07.525
For us, it's fine to think in those terms,

31
00:02:07.525 --> 00:02:12.408
to picture a stay-at-home mum or
whatever else.

32
00:02:12.408 --> 00:02:17.942
But in terms of how you decide to split
out your audience, you wanna split them

33
00:02:17.942 --> 00:02:23.840
out based on different criteria to things
like demographics and stuff like that.

34
00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:28.508
So for example,
different questions, right?

35
00:02:28.508 --> 00:02:33.759
If there's an audience that
has a certain set of questions

36
00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:38.903
that they come to your app with or
certain objections, or

37
00:02:38.903 --> 00:02:45.994
certain challenges that they face,
then that makes a good audience, right?

38
00:02:45.994 --> 00:02:48.524
To segment them in that regards.

39
00:02:48.524 --> 00:02:51.852
Tasks is another really good example,
right?

40
00:02:51.852 --> 00:02:56.935
If an audience wants to complete
different tasks to another audience,

41
00:02:56.935 --> 00:03:00.083
that's a good way of splitting it, right?

42
00:03:00.083 --> 00:03:06.095
Or they've got different needs, then you
wanna split it along those lines as well.

43
00:03:06.095 --> 00:03:11.927
So that task app example I gave from
earlier is a really good example of this.

44
00:03:11.927 --> 00:03:18.323
That project managers,
stay at home mums and a freelancer for

45
00:03:18.323 --> 00:03:25.339
example, that would be an obvious
way of splitting your audience.

46
00:03:25.339 --> 00:03:28.237
Because freelancer, project managers and

47
00:03:28.237 --> 00:03:32.385
stay at home moms have very
different questions that they ask,

48
00:03:32.385 --> 00:03:37.572
very different tasks they wanna complete,
and very different needs, okay?

49
00:03:37.572 --> 00:03:42.593
Well, if you looked at it from
a purely demographic point of view,

50
00:03:42.593 --> 00:03:46.362
actually they could have
all ended up falling into

51
00:03:46.362 --> 00:03:50.594
the same demographic of
certain socioeconomic group.

52
00:03:50.594 --> 00:03:55.621
But it's their needs that define them
rather than their demographics is,

53
00:03:55.621 --> 00:03:57.793
I guess, what I'm getting at.

54
00:03:57.793 --> 00:04:03.392
So looking at your audience in
those terms is very important.

55
00:04:03.392 --> 00:04:07.504
You might also wanna
consider the other little

56
00:04:07.504 --> 00:04:11.100
aspect of this is usage level of the app.

57
00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:15.087
So, if someone is just
using the app occasionally,

58
00:04:15.087 --> 00:04:18.439
then they are gonna have
different needs and

59
00:04:18.439 --> 00:04:23.439
different requirements to somebody
who's using it regularly.

60
00:04:23.439 --> 00:04:27.878
Equally, somebody who's using it for the
first time is gonna have very different

61
00:04:27.878 --> 00:04:31.030
needs to somebody who's been using it for
donkeys years or

62
00:04:31.030 --> 00:04:32.919
different perspective, right?

63
00:04:32.919 --> 00:04:37.798
So it's hard for me to give specific
advice about how you segment, but

64
00:04:37.798 --> 00:04:41.025
thinking around those needs,
those tasks and

65
00:04:41.025 --> 00:04:44.760
those questions will get
you in the right direction.

66
00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:49.904
And then once that has been done,
then it's a matter of beginning to

67
00:04:49.904 --> 00:04:55.153
